RED FLAG 1 — Mandatory Excel marker footnote parsing
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Bug: Excel quantity cells with markers (*, #, $, @, etc.) require footnote 
text to parse correctly. Two failure modes:

Case A (Trilaciclib): "349*" for salt-form API. Excel has no footnote. User 
asked for salt_factor, guessed 1.4 (wrong). Correct value from footnote 
would be 1.163. All Amount in Max Dose values off by 1.203x.

Case B (Epinephrine): "1.10*" for 10% overage on API. Excel has no footnote. 
Volume-based dosing (mg/mL) naturally captured overage in this case — math 
worked coincidentally. But same class of missing-context bug.

Case C (q.s. markers): "@" on Water for Injection, "Qs to adjust pH" on HCl. 
Standard q.s. notation — needs recognition to render "NA" cells correctly.

Architectural fix: Make Excel footnotes mandatory when markers present. Parse 
footnote content to classify purpose. Route to appropriate handler.

Fix in residual_solvent.py:

1. Add parse_composition_footnotes(excel_bytes):
Scan all cells across all sheets for marker-marked quantity cells.
Supported markers: *, **, ***, #, ##, $, @, †, ‡, § (all footnote symbols).
Record: ingredient_name, quantity_value, marker_symbol, sheet, row.

Scan all cells for footnote text starting with matching marker.
Classify footnote purpose into 4 categories:

Category A — Salt/base equivalence:
Patterns:
- "X mg of [salt] is equivalent to Y mg [base]"
- "X mg of [salt] contains Y mg [base]"
- "X mg of [salt] equals Y mg [base]"
- "* Corresponding to Y mg [base]"
- "* Expressed as [base name]"
Extracted values: salt_qty (X), base_qty (Y), salt_name, base_name
Compute: salt_factor = salt_qty / base_qty

Category B — Overage:
Patterns:
- "X% overage of API"
- "includes overage of X%"
- "Y mg per mL includes X% overage"
- "manufacturing overage of X%"
Extracted values: overage_pct (X)
Compute: effective_qty = declared_qty / (1 + overage_pct/100)

Category C — q.s. notation:
Patterns:
- "Qs to adjust pH to X"
- "Qs to X mL"
- "Qs to make X mL"
- "q.s.", "q. s.", "Q.s"
- "quantity sufficient"
Set: is_qs flag on the row

Category D — Informational:
Any other footnote text (preservative note, adjustment note, etc.)
Log for audit; no math effect

Return: matched_entries with classification per marker, unmatched_markers 
for validation errors.

2. Add validate_excel_footnotes(excel_bytes):
Wraps parse_composition_footnotes. Raise ExcelValidationError if:
- Marker present on quantity cell but no matching footnote text
- Category A footnote present but cannot extract salt_qty AND base_qty
- Category B footnote present but cannot extract overage percentage

Provide clear error message with:
- Which ingredients have unmatched markers
- Required footnote format examples for each category
- Reference to approved TSR footnote convention

3. In app.py _run_residual_solvent_workflow:
BEFORE classify_rs_excel, call validate_excel_footnotes.
Block workflow on validation errors with UI error message.

On validation pass:
- Category A entries → set salt_factor, base_qty per ingredient
- Category B entries → set overage_pct per ingredient
- Category C entries → flag is_qs on row (renders "NA")
- Pass to parse_single_strength_unit_composition (never ask user)

4. UI simplification:
Remove salt_factor field from Advanced section.
Remove overage_pct field from Advanced section.

Keep only:
- Maximum Daily Dose input (single field)
* If unit basis = "mg/vial" or "mg/tablet" or "mg/capsule": ask in mg/day
* If unit basis = "mg/mL": ask in mL/day
* If unit basis = "mg/sachet": ask in sachets/day
- Density input (only shown for mg/mL unit basis — optional override, see 
Red Flag 2)

Show detected marker classifications in info panel (informational, not a 
confirmation gate):
"Auto-detected markers:
* on 'Trilaciclib 2HCl' (349 mg/vial) → Salt/base equivalence
Salt: 349 mg dihydrochloride ≡ Base: 300 mg (factor 1.163)
# on 'Chlorobutanol' (5.25 mg/mL) → Informational note
@ on 'Water for Injection' → q.s. marker (NA cells)"

